{"cues": [{"duration": 4.311, "start": 11.88, "text": "In the last video, along with the ideas of vector addition and scalar multiplication, "}, {"duration": 3.761, "start": 16.191, "text": "I described vector coordinates, where there's this back and forth between, "}, {"duration": 2.908, "start": 19.952, "text": "for example, pairs of numbers and two-dimensional vectors."}, {"duration": 3.236, "start": 23.8, "text": "Now, I imagine the vector coordinates were already familiar to a lot of you, "}, {"duration": 3.278, "start": 27.036, "text": "but there's another kind of interesting way to think about these coordinates, "}, {"duration": 1.766, "start": 30.314, "text": "which is pretty central to linear algebra."}, {"duration": 3.707, "start": 32.84, "text": "When you have a pair of numbers that's meant to describe a vector, "}, {"duration": 4.151, "start": 36.547, "text": "like 3, negative 2, I want you to think about each coordinate as a scalar, "}, {"duration": 3.542, "start": 40.698, "text": "meaning, think about how each one stretches or squishes vectors."}, {"duration": 3.701, "start": 45.14, "text": "In the xy coordinate system, there are two very special vectors, "}, {"duration": 3.871, "start": 48.841, "text": "the one pointing to the right with length 1, commonly called i-hat, "}, {"duration": 4.954, "start": 52.712, "text": "or the unit vector in the x direction, and the one pointing straight up with length 1, "}, {"duration": 3.474, "start": 57.666, "text": "commonly called j-hat, or the unit vector in the y direction."}, {"duration": 4.332, "start": 62.44, "text": "Now, think of the x coordinate of our vector as a scalar that scales i-hat, "}, {"duration": 4.788, "start": 66.772, "text": "stretching it by a factor of 3, and the y coordinate as a scalar that scales j-hat, "}, {"duration": 2.68, "start": 71.56, "text": "flipping it and stretching it by a factor of 2."}, {"duration": 2.94, "start": 74.88, "text": "In this sense, the vector that these coordinates "}, {"duration": 2.52, "start": 77.82, "text": "describe is the sum of two scaled vectors."}, {"duration": 5.22, "start": 80.34, "text": "That's a surprisingly important concept, this idea of adding together two scaled vectors."}, {"duration": 3.12, "start": 87.32, "text": "Those two vectors, i-hat and j-hat, have a special name, by the way."}, {"duration": 2.66, "start": 90.9, "text": "Together, they're called the basis of a coordinate system."}, {"duration": 4.06, "start": 94.24, "text": "What this means, basically, is that when you think about coordinates as scalars, "}, {"duration": 3.36, "start": 98.3, "text": "the basis vectors are what those scalars actually, you know, scale."}, {"duration": 3.34, "start": 102.32, "text": "There's also a more technical definition, but I'll get to that later."}, {"duration": 4.172, "start": 107.18, "text": "By framing our coordinate system in terms of these two special basis vectors, "}, {"duration": 2.568, "start": 111.352, "text": "it raises a pretty interesting and subtle point."}, {"duration": 2.911, "start": 114.46, "text": "We could have chosen different basis vectors and "}, {"duration": 3.149, "start": 117.371, "text": "gotten a completely reasonable new coordinate system."}, {"duration": 2.663, "start": 121.1, "text": "For example, take some vector pointing up and to the right, "}, {"duration": 3.197, "start": 123.763, "text": "along with some other vector pointing down and to the right in some way."}, {"duration": 4.817, "start": 127.62, "text": "Take a moment to think about all the different vectors that you can get by choosing two "}, {"duration": 4.763, "start": 132.437, "text": "scalars, using each one to scale one of the vectors, then adding together what you get."}, {"duration": 3.58, "start": 137.92, "text": "Which two-dimensional vectors can you reach by altering the choices of scalars?"}, {"duration": 3.588, "start": 144.58, "text": "The answer is that you can reach every possible two-dimensional vector, "}, {"duration": 2.492, "start": 148.168, "text": "and I think it's a good puzzle to contemplate why."}, {"duration": 4.502, "start": 152.32, "text": "A new pair of basis vectors like this still gives us a valid way to go back and forth "}, {"duration": 2.827, "start": 156.822, "text": "between pairs of numbers and two-dimensional vectors, "}, {"duration": 4.45, "start": 159.649, "text": "but the association is definitely different from the one that you get using the more "}, {"duration": 1.781, "start": 164.099, "text": "standard basis of i-hat and j-hat."}, {"duration": 2.865, "start": 166.46, "text": "This is something I'll go into much more detail on later, "}, {"duration": 3.557, "start": 169.325, "text": "describing the exact relationship between different coordinate systems, "}, {"duration": 3.705, "start": 172.882, "text": "but for right now, I just want you to appreciate the fact that any time we "}, {"duration": 3.804, "start": 176.587, "text": "describe vectors numerically, it depends on an implicit choice of what basis "}, {"duration": 0.989, "start": 180.391, "text": "vectors we're using."}, {"duration": 3.612, "start": 182.36, "text": "So any time that you're scaling two vectors and adding them like this, "}, {"duration": 2.748, "start": 185.972, "text": "it's called a linear combination of those two vectors."}, {"duration": 1.54, "start": 191.12, "text": "Where does this word linear come from?"}, {"duration": 1.56, "start": 192.84, "text": "Why does this have anything to do with lines?"}, {"duration": 3.509, "start": 194.94, "text": "Well, this isn't the etymology, but one way I like to think about it "}, {"duration": 4.424, "start": 198.449, "text": "is that if you fix one of those scalars and let the other one change its value freely, "}, {"duration": 2.747, "start": 202.873, "text": "the tip of the resulting vector draws a straight line."}, {"duration": 3.351, "start": 209.16, "text": "Now, if you let both scalars range freely and consider every possible "}, {"duration": 2.969, "start": 212.511, "text": "vector that you can get, there are two things that can happen."}, {"duration": 3.88, "start": 216.24, "text": "For most pairs of vectors, you'll be able to reach every possible point in the plane."}, {"duration": 2.34, "start": 220.6, "text": "Every two-dimensional vector is within your grasp."}, {"duration": 4.022, "start": 223.56, "text": "However, in the unlucky case where your two original vectors happen to line up, "}, {"duration": 4.426, "start": 227.582, "text": "the tip of the resulting vector is limited to just this single line passing through the "}, {"duration": 0.352, "start": 232.008, "text": "origin."}, {"duration": 2.14, "start": 233.98, "text": "Actually, technically there's a third possibility too."}, {"duration": 3.68, "start": 236.48, "text": "Both your vectors could be zero, in which case you'd just be stuck at the origin."}, {"duration": 0.98, "start": 241.4, "text": "Here's some more terminology."}, {"duration": 4.331, "start": 242.84, "text": "The set of all possible vectors that you can reach with a linear combination "}, {"duration": 3.769, "start": 247.171, "text": "of a given pair of vectors is called the span of those two vectors."}, {"duration": 3.603, "start": 254.68, "text": "So restating what we just saw in this lingo, the span of most "}, {"duration": 4.126, "start": 258.283, "text": "pairs of 2D vectors is all vectors of 2D space, but when they line up, "}, {"duration": 3.371, "start": 262.409, "text": "their span is all vectors whose tip sit on a certain line."}, {"duration": 2.12, "start": 267.16, "text": "Remember how I said that linear algebra revolves "}, {"duration": 2.12, "start": 269.28, "text": "around vector addition and scalar multiplication?"}, {"duration": 3.45, "start": 271.96, "text": "Well, the span of two vectors is basically a way of asking what "}, {"duration": 4.745, "start": 275.41, "text": "are all the possible vectors you can reach using only these two fundamental operations, "}, {"duration": 2.265, "start": 280.155, "text": "vector addition and scalar multiplication."}, {"duration": 3.6, "start": 283.62, "text": "This is a good time to talk about how people commonly think about vectors as points."}, {"duration": 3.991, "start": 287.94, "text": "It gets really crowded to think about a whole collection of vectors sitting on a line, "}, {"duration": 3.625, "start": 291.931, "text": "and more crowded still to think about all two-dimensional vectors all at once, "}, {"duration": 0.964, "start": 295.556, "text": "filling up the plane."}, {"duration": 2.903, "start": 297.22, "text": "So when dealing with collections of vectors like this, "}, {"duration": 3.274, "start": 300.123, "text": "it's common to represent each one with just a point in space, "}, {"duration": 2.798, "start": 303.397, "text": "the point at the tip of that vector where, as usual, "}, {"duration": 3.485, "start": 306.195, "text": "I want you thinking about that vector with its tail on the origin."}, {"duration": 3.487, "start": 310.58, "text": "That way, if you want to think about every possible vector whose "}, {"duration": 3.273, "start": 314.067, "text": "tip sits on a certain line, just think about the line itself."}, {"duration": 4.257, "start": 319.98, "text": "Likewise, to think about all possible two-dimensional vectors all at once, "}, {"duration": 3.123, "start": 324.237, "text": "conceptualize each one as the point where its tip sits."}, {"duration": 3.43, "start": 327.36, "text": "So in effect, what you'll be thinking about is the infinite flat "}, {"duration": 3.59, "start": 330.79, "text": "sheet of two-dimensional space itself, leaving the arrows out of it."}, {"duration": 3.6, "start": 336.14, "text": "In general, if you're thinking about a vector on its own, think of it as an arrow."}, {"duration": 2.237, "start": 340.16, "text": "And if you're dealing with a collection of vectors, "}, {"duration": 2.023, "start": 342.397, "text": "it's convenient to think of them all as points."}, {"duration": 3.447, "start": 345.24, "text": "So for our span example, the span of most pairs of vectors ends "}, {"duration": 3.233, "start": 348.687, "text": "up being the entire infinite sheet of two-dimensional space."}, {"duration": 2.7, "start": 352.18, "text": "But if they line up, their span is just a line."}, {"duration": 2.459, "start": 358.2, "text": "The idea of span gets a lot more interesting if we "}, {"duration": 2.701, "start": 360.659, "text": "start thinking about vectors in three-dimensional space."}, {"duration": 3.17, "start": 364.08, "text": "For example, if you take two vectors in 3D space that are not "}, {"duration": 3.53, "start": 367.25, "text": "pointing in the same direction, what does it mean to take their span?"}, {"duration": 4.006, "start": 373.34, "text": "Well, their span is the collection of all possible linear combinations "}, {"duration": 3.949, "start": 377.346, "text": "of those two vectors, meaning all possible vectors you get by scaling "}, {"duration": 3.725, "start": 381.295, "text": "each of the two of them in some way and then adding them together."}, {"duration": 3.177, "start": 385.78, "text": "You can kind of imagine turning two different knobs to change "}, {"duration": 2.512, "start": 388.957, "text": "the two scalars defining the linear combination, "}, {"duration": 3.691, "start": 391.469, "text": "adding the scaled vectors and following the tip of the resulting vector."}, {"duration": 2.39, "start": 396.04, "text": "That tip will trace out some kind of flat sheet "}, {"duration": 2.69, "start": 398.43, "text": "cutting through the origin of three-dimensional space."}, {"duration": 2.62, "start": 401.94, "text": "This flat sheet is the span of the two vectors."}, {"duration": 2.981, "start": 405.12, "text": "Or more precisely, the set of all possible vectors whose "}, {"duration": 3.139, "start": 408.101, "text": "tips sit on that flat sheet is the span of your two vectors."}, {"duration": 1.48, "start": 411.88, "text": "Isn't that a beautiful mental image?"}, {"duration": 2.466, "start": 414.48, "text": "So, what happens if we add a third vector and "}, {"duration": 2.414, "start": 416.946, "text": "consider the span of all three of those guys?"}, {"duration": 2.304, "start": 420.7, "text": "A linear combination of three vectors is defined "}, {"duration": 1.976, "start": 423.004, "text": "pretty much the same way as it is for two."}, {"duration": 3.75, "start": 425.38, "text": "You'll choose three different scalars, scale each of those vectors, "}, {"duration": 1.71, "start": 429.13, "text": "and then add them all together."}, {"duration": 4.98, "start": 435.98, "text": "And again, the span of these vectors is the set of all possible linear combinations."}, {"duration": 1.64, "start": 444.32, "text": "Two different things could happen here."}, {"duration": 3.735, "start": 446.32, "text": "If your third vector happens to be sitting on the span of the first two, "}, {"duration": 1.485, "start": 450.055, "text": "then the span doesn't change."}, {"duration": 2.12, "start": 451.82, "text": "You're sort of trapped on that same flat sheet."}, {"duration": 3.285, "start": 454.5, "text": "In other words, adding a scaled version of that third vector to the "}, {"duration": 3.335, "start": 457.785, "text": "linear combination doesn't really give you access to any new vectors."}, {"duration": 2.268, "start": 462.72, "text": "But if you just randomly choose a third vector, "}, {"duration": 3.072, "start": 464.988, "text": "it's almost certainly not sitting on the span of those first two."}, {"duration": 2.559, "start": 468.7, "text": "Then, since it's pointing in a separate direction, "}, {"duration": 3.061, "start": 471.259, "text": "it unlocks access to every possible three-dimensional vector."}, {"duration": 4.369, "start": 475.52, "text": "One way I like to think about this is that as you scale that new third vector, "}, {"duration": 4.591, "start": 479.889, "text": "it moves around that span sheet of the first two, sweeping it through all of space."}, {"duration": 4.262, "start": 485.9, "text": "Another way to think about it is that you're making full use of the three freely changing "}, {"duration": 3.978, "start": 490.162, "text": "scalars that you have at your disposal to access the full three dimensions of space."}, {"duration": 4.425, "start": 496.64, "text": "Now, in the case where the third vector was already sitting on the span of the first two, "}, {"duration": 2.41, "start": 501.065, "text": "or the case where two vectors happen to line up, "}, {"duration": 4.13, "start": 503.475, "text": "we want some terminology to describe the fact that at least one of these vectors is "}, {"duration": 2.115, "start": 507.605, "text": "redundant, not adding anything to our span."}, {"duration": 4.324, "start": 510.82, "text": "Whenever this happens, where you have multiple vectors and you could remove one without "}, {"duration": 4.275, "start": 515.144, "text": "reducing the span, the relevant terminology is to say that they are linearly dependent."}, {"duration": 4.198, "start": 520.38, "text": "Another way of phrasing that would be to say that one of the vectors can be expressed "}, {"duration": 4.102, "start": 524.578, "text": "as a linear combination of the others, since it's already in the span of the others."}, {"duration": 4.444, "start": 532.98, "text": "On the other hand, if each vector really does add another dimension to the span, "}, {"duration": 2.196, "start": 537.424, "text": "they're said to be linearly independent."}, {"duration": 3.036, "start": 546.34, "text": "So with all of that terminology, and hopefully with some good mental "}, {"duration": 2.904, "start": 549.376, "text": "images to go with it, let me leave you with a puzzle before we go."}, {"duration": 3.768, "start": 552.28, "text": "The technical definition of a basis of a space is a "}, {"duration": 4.132, "start": 556.048, "text": "set of linearly independent vectors that span that space."}, {"duration": 4.885, "start": 562.04, "text": "Now, given how I described a basis earlier, and given your current understanding of the "}, {"duration": 4.775, "start": 566.925, "text": "words span and linearly independent, think about why this definition would make sense."}, {"duration": 4.0, "start": 573.88, "text": "In the next video, I'll get into matrices in transforming space. See you then!"}], "video_id": "k7RM-ot2NWY"}